WEBVTT

00:01.000 --> 00:04.040
Mr Shelby, you're not yourself.
I should call a doctor.

00:04.160 --> 00:07.480
It's just myself talking to myself
about myself.

00:07.600 --> 00:10.280
Michael, you're going to New York.

00:10.400 --> 00:11.400
Why?

00:11.520 --> 00:15.280
Because the company has business
to attend to in America.

00:15.400 --> 00:17.680
You knew I was going to be shot...

00:18.920 --> 00:21.040
...and you chose not to tell me.

00:22.280 --> 00:23.640
I chose my mum.

00:25.280 --> 00:29.960
RETURNING OFFICER:
<i>Thomas Shelby, Labour Party, 48,564!</i>

00:30.080 --> 00:32.600
(CHEERING)

00:36.720 --> 00:38.400
I've been to a doctor on your behalf.

00:38.520 --> 00:41.960
It starts when you stop. When you rest.

00:44.720 --> 00:47.320
(VOICES ECHO)

00:57.000 --> 00:59.320
Mr Shelby, you're meant to be resting.

01:01.760 --> 01:03.560
I have learnt something, Frances.

01:05.080 --> 01:08.480
There's no rest for me in this world.

01:08.600 --> 01:10.600
<i>Perhaps in the next.</i>

01:21.560 --> 01:24.120
(WIND WHISTLES)

01:41.520 --> 01:43.680
(PHONE RINGS IN THE DISTANCE)

02:29.280 --> 02:30.320
Arthur.

02:30.440 --> 02:33.720
"We cannot give you the assurance
you are asking for.

02:35.280 --> 02:38.000
"We expect payment in full."

02:39.480 --> 02:41.280
Here's my favourite part.

02:42.520 --> 02:46.880
"We have never even heard
of your people,

02:47.000 --> 02:51.280
"so we are not afraid of your threats."

02:51.400 --> 02:57.320
And they've signed it
"the Angels of Retribution".

02:59.680 --> 03:01.120
Hm.

03:29.480 --> 03:31.320
They say
they haven't even heard of us.

03:31.440 --> 03:34.960
So tell Aberama and Isiah to
introduce themselves.

03:35.080 --> 03:36.440
And, Finn...

03:36.560 --> 03:37.560
...you stay out of it.

04:40.320 --> 04:42.400
(PHONE RINGS)

04:50.840 --> 04:52.920
(RINGING CONTINUES)

05:14.760 --> 05:15.960
Yeah.

05:19.600 --> 05:20.920
Wait.

05:21.040 --> 05:22.600
Wait, wait. Say that again.

05:25.400 --> 05:26.720
No.

05:26.840 --> 05:28.480
No, that cannot be possible!

05:37.080 --> 05:38.960
(MOANS SOFTLY)

05:53.360 --> 05:56.880
Peter, my beautiful pilot...

06:01.520 --> 06:07.720
Now will you please fly me
and my winnings back to England?

06:09.120 --> 06:10.880
(DOG BARKS)

06:18.960 --> 06:21.120
Ten spoonfuls of sugar for me, please.

06:22.480 --> 06:23.920
Where's that full one?

06:24.040 --> 06:25.840
Look, Ruby.

06:25.960 --> 06:27.480
Daddy's back from his call.

06:28.840 --> 06:32.800
Everything's going to be all right now.

07:21.160 --> 07:23.240
(DOOR CRASHES)

07:36.880 --> 07:38.800
Oh, no, no.

07:38.920 --> 07:40.440
No, no, no, no, no, no.

07:41.760 --> 07:43.920
(RAPID TICKING)

07:50.560 --> 07:53.200
Oh, no, no.

07:53.320 --> 07:55.120
(INHALES)

07:55.240 --> 07:56.240
Ah!

07:58.440 --> 08:00.720
- (PHONE RINGS)
- Hello?

08:00.840 --> 08:02.640
Arthur! Arthur, where's Tommy?

08:09.400 --> 08:11.520
Just get to him and tell him
that we've lost the lot.

08:11.640 --> 08:13.560
Stay there. You stay put.

08:13.680 --> 08:15.600
You'll hear from Tommy.

08:17.160 --> 08:19.400
Arthur, what are you talking about?
How is that possible?

08:19.520 --> 08:21.400
<i>It's possible because, this morning</i>

08:21.520 --> 08:23.880
in New York City at 6am,

08:24.000 --> 08:27.480
the Wall Street Stock Exchange crashed

08:27.600 --> 08:29.400
<i>like a steam train.</i>

08:29.520 --> 08:31.840
We were most definitely on board.

08:31.960 --> 08:35.560
(SHOUTING AND SCREAMING)

08:39.880 --> 08:41.640
Fuck it.

08:41.760 --> 08:43.960
(CONFUSED SHOUTING)

08:54.960 --> 08:57.240
- Oi! Come on, get changed!
- Jesus Christ!

08:57.360 --> 08:58.840
Bring the car round!

08:58.960 --> 09:01.000
(WOMEN SHOUT)

09:06.640 --> 09:09.320
We've got to get out of here.
Hurry up. Come on!

09:09.440 --> 09:11.560
I'm going!

09:11.680 --> 09:14.560
Change of plan.
We're not going to London any more.

09:14.680 --> 09:17.640
- We're going straight to Birmingham.
- There are other passengers.

09:17.760 --> 09:18.720
Not any more.

09:18.840 --> 09:21.080
(CHILD CRIES)

09:46.800 --> 09:48.720
If you're going to England,
I'm coming with you.

09:48.840 --> 09:50.800
- No. No.
- I love you, you love me.

09:50.920 --> 09:53.440
- That's the truth.
- Gina, wait, come on.

09:53.560 --> 09:55.120
I want to meet your family.

09:55.240 --> 09:56.280
No, you don't.

10:04.520 --> 10:06.720
(GUNSHOT)

10:10.760 --> 10:11.680
(GUNSHOT)

10:11.800 --> 10:12.800
Argh!

10:40.320 --> 10:42.240
Now you've heard of us.

10:44.760 --> 10:45.760
(GUNSHOT)

10:51.960 --> 10:53.600
Come on.

10:53.720 --> 10:55.320
Couch. Couch!

10:55.440 --> 10:58.880
Put something down for the blood.
My sister'll fucking kill me.

10:59.000 --> 11:00.600
- (GLASS SMASHES)
- Be fucking careful.

11:00.720 --> 11:02.880
She spends thousands of pounds
on this shit.

11:03.000 --> 11:04.400
Argh!

11:04.520 --> 11:07.000
- Get me some booze.
- Ah!

11:10.120 --> 11:11.720
(FINN SCREAMS IN AGONY)

11:11.840 --> 11:14.040
Just fucking get the thing out of me
and sew me up.

11:14.160 --> 11:15.280
Just do it.

11:18.360 --> 11:20.120
Peaky boy, give me your blade.

11:26.360 --> 11:27.640
That's enough.

11:27.760 --> 11:30.120
Don't want you throwing up
on your sister's furniture.

11:30.240 --> 11:31.720
(FINN WHIMPERS)

11:31.840 --> 11:35.040
- You know what you're doing?
- I've done this a thousand times.

11:35.160 --> 11:39.120
I once took a bullet from between
two ribs, one inch from the heart.

11:39.240 --> 11:40.680
Mind you, it was a horse.

11:40.800 --> 11:42.560
And the horse did die.

11:42.680 --> 11:44.240
Hold him. Hold him.

11:45.440 --> 11:46.640
(FINN GROANS)

11:52.800 --> 11:54.200
(FINN PANTS)

11:57.120 --> 11:58.040
There you go.

11:58.160 --> 11:59.400
Just a little one.

12:01.000 --> 12:04.640
- What the fuck is going on?
- Oh, fuck.

12:04.760 --> 12:06.480
Hello, Ada.

12:06.600 --> 12:08.960
Get out, both of you.

12:17.000 --> 12:18.040
Push this on the wound.

12:18.160 --> 12:19.800
- Keep up the pressure.
- Get out.

12:21.400 --> 12:22.360
I'm so sorry, Ada.

12:22.480 --> 12:24.880
They broke a statue of some thin woman.

12:25.000 --> 12:27.080
Fucking statues.

12:27.200 --> 12:28.920
What has Tommy told you?

12:29.040 --> 12:31.600
- Shelbys stay out of the sporting stuff.
- What?

12:31.720 --> 12:34.080
- To maintain his fucking reputation?
- Oi!

12:35.120 --> 12:36.520
You listen to me.

12:36.640 --> 12:37.760
We've got a chance.

12:37.880 --> 12:40.320
Tommy has given us that chance.

12:40.440 --> 12:44.480
He's got power, we've got money
and our past is left behind us.

12:44.600 --> 12:48.040
And you've got a precious young life,
Finn, you fucking idiot.

12:48.160 --> 12:50.160
Three inches to the left
and that would have been gone.

12:50.280 --> 12:51.280
(FINN WINCES)

12:54.040 --> 12:56.440
You've got nothing to prove, Finn.

12:56.560 --> 12:59.520
You have got nothing to prove.

13:06.920 --> 13:09.120
Daddy! Daddy!

13:09.240 --> 13:11.600
Come here, you. Come here. Come here.
Come here. Come here. Come here.

13:11.720 --> 13:12.920
Ooh!

13:13.040 --> 13:15.640
Now, what have you been up to, eh?

13:15.760 --> 13:17.000
Get it done, Johnny.

13:20.720 --> 13:22.600
All right, you heard the man. Let's go.

13:31.080 --> 13:32.760
Where's Charles?

13:32.880 --> 13:35.360
He's in the wagon. He won't come out.

13:35.480 --> 13:37.400
He heard Johnny talking Rokker.

13:37.520 --> 13:39.880
He understands more Gypsy
than we think.

13:40.000 --> 13:42.000
He heard him say you shot the horse.

13:42.120 --> 13:45.200
I told him it was mercy. I said
it's what you do when a horse gets sick.

13:45.320 --> 13:46.600
He doesn't understand.

13:47.920 --> 13:50.880
Dad, why did you shoot him?

13:55.000 --> 13:58.120
Charlie, get out here now.
Let's get it done.

13:58.240 --> 13:59.240
(HORSE NEIGHS)

14:00.280 --> 14:02.520
Charles? Come here.

14:05.720 --> 14:07.000
Sit down.

14:11.840 --> 14:13.000
Now, listen to me.

14:15.360 --> 14:18.040
Your horse was sick. He was in pain.

14:18.160 --> 14:20.360
The vet couldn't do anything,
even Curly couldn't do anything.

14:20.480 --> 14:21.680
I put him to sleep.

14:22.800 --> 14:24.360
- It's what you do.
- No!

14:24.480 --> 14:25.880
It's what <i>you</i> do.

14:26.000 --> 14:30.640
Shoot horses, shoot people.
Everybody says.

15:08.920 --> 15:10.800
Dangerous, my beautiful horse.

15:13.640 --> 15:14.960
Too wild to race.

15:16.480 --> 15:18.000
Wouldn't take the reins or the whip.

15:20.320 --> 15:21.920
Should have been a war horse.

15:23.800 --> 15:25.240
Got tired of the pasture.

15:27.960 --> 15:30.480
Couldn't stick the peace and quiet,
gave up on life...

15:32.160 --> 15:33.440
...and is now free.

15:37.920 --> 15:38.920
In the bleak...

15:43.920 --> 15:45.000
You're crying.

16:18.760 --> 16:19.760
Tom...

16:20.840 --> 16:21.880
...I'm sorry.

16:22.000 --> 16:24.920
- I didn't know your boy spoke Rokker.
- (HORN BEEPS)

16:25.040 --> 16:26.520
Fill it in, Johnny.

16:32.320 --> 16:33.320
It's fine.

16:34.440 --> 16:36.800
I've called the house, the office.

16:36.920 --> 16:38.680
But if I tell you...

16:40.280 --> 16:41.520
...you won't believe it...

16:44.080 --> 16:45.600
...so I'll show you.

16:45.720 --> 16:46.720
Huh?

16:59.840 --> 17:03.000
I told Michael on Friday
this was going to happen.

17:03.120 --> 17:04.880
Yeah.

17:05.000 --> 17:11.520
Fucking Michael...said he was advised
by the broker that prices would rebound.

17:11.640 --> 17:13.920
Everybody was told the same thing.

17:18.360 --> 17:19.440
He held on.

17:25.960 --> 17:27.440
- Michael held on?
- Yeah.

17:36.080 --> 17:37.320
Michael.

17:44.600 --> 17:47.640
- Michael held on?
- Yeah.

17:50.640 --> 17:51.880
Michael held on...

17:53.520 --> 17:56.600
...and carried on dancing and playing...

17:57.840 --> 17:59.360
...and fucking in the snow.

18:01.200 --> 18:02.480
Charlie!

18:04.160 --> 18:05.680
Charlie, come out here now!

18:07.040 --> 18:08.840
Kid never fucking listens.

18:08.960 --> 18:11.040
Never listens, Lizzie.

18:12.880 --> 18:18.920
(SHOUTS) What do I have to do
to make people fucking listen to me?!

18:19.040 --> 18:21.160
Holy fuck.

18:21.280 --> 18:23.040
What do we do now, Tommy, eh?

18:26.760 --> 18:27.800
What do we do?

18:32.240 --> 18:37.680
Lizzie, you go with Arthur to Birmingham,
you stay in the Midland Hotel.

18:37.800 --> 18:42.520
Arthur, call a full meeting of
the board of directors tomorrow at noon.

18:42.640 --> 18:44.360
A full fucking meeting.

18:44.480 --> 18:47.160
What about today, eh?
What's wrong with today, Tom?

18:47.280 --> 18:49.360
- I need to do some thinking.
- Oh, yeah.

18:49.480 --> 18:51.040
Oh, you do that best on your own,

18:51.160 --> 18:53.960
- don't you, eh?
- I won't be on my own. Never on my own.

18:54.080 --> 18:57.840
Lizzie, you have the driver
come back tomorrow.

18:57.960 --> 19:01.040
And, Arthur, tell my boy...

19:02.080 --> 19:05.520
...that sometimes death is a kindness.

19:05.640 --> 19:06.840
Come on.

19:57.880 --> 19:58.880
<i>What now?</i>

20:00.680 --> 20:02.240
GRACE: What am I, a genie?

20:02.360 --> 20:04.640
You summon me up
with your little bottle of dope.

20:06.440 --> 20:10.800
I take it for the pain, to keep warm.

20:18.800 --> 20:20.160
Is that what it's for?

20:21.560 --> 20:22.560
The warmth?

20:25.920 --> 20:26.960
(WHISPERS) The warmth.

20:30.760 --> 20:32.040
All this time.

20:33.920 --> 20:34.920
I know.

20:37.880 --> 20:39.680
Our love still remains.

20:43.600 --> 20:46.000
But you have to listen
to the voices that you hear.

20:49.240 --> 20:50.680
Do what they tell you to do.

20:53.520 --> 20:55.040
Too much to do, Grace.

20:57.600 --> 20:58.960
The kids.

21:03.720 --> 21:05.720
I need to say goodbye.

21:08.720 --> 21:10.360
I need to sleep.

21:12.360 --> 21:13.440
Just think, Tom.

21:24.840 --> 21:26.000
ARTHUR: Linda!

21:26.120 --> 21:27.720
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACH)

21:28.880 --> 21:30.480
(DOOR OPENS)

21:31.720 --> 21:35.840
Oh, there you are, eh?

21:35.960 --> 21:37.680
(LOCKS DOOR)

21:39.920 --> 21:42.920
You're the chairman, Arthur,
so start acting like one.

21:43.040 --> 21:44.400
Chairman, am I, hm?

21:46.800 --> 21:47.920
No.

21:49.040 --> 21:53.080
I'm the fucking doorman, Linda, hm?

21:54.360 --> 21:57.160
And you ain't coming in here tonight,
love, dressed like that.

22:00.640 --> 22:02.880
Tommy made me chairman so that...

22:05.000 --> 22:06.360
...he could stay clean.

22:09.120 --> 22:10.480
It's called an arrangement.

22:11.560 --> 22:12.800
It's an opportunity.

22:25.440 --> 22:28.080
I know who I am, Linda.

22:31.160 --> 22:33.360
I know who I am and I'm all right with it.

22:34.720 --> 22:35.800
Finally.

22:37.680 --> 22:38.920
I can live with it.

22:52.920 --> 22:54.680
I need you to be all right with it.

22:58.800 --> 23:02.720
I need you to be all right with it, eh?

23:02.840 --> 23:05.040
What is it, eh?

23:06.440 --> 23:07.680
And what do you want, hm?

23:09.400 --> 23:11.880
What, do you want the chairman?
Do you? Hmm?

23:12.960 --> 23:17.920
With his fancy briefcase
and his gold fountain pen, eh?

23:20.440 --> 23:21.640
What do you want?

23:23.160 --> 23:24.160
Chairman...

23:25.480 --> 23:27.560
...or doorman? Hm?

23:27.680 --> 23:31.960
You think we can fuck and it'll be OK
and I'll be quiet. Well, I won't.

23:33.720 --> 23:37.080
Every week, your brother's down in London,
making out he's fucking Robin Hood,

23:37.200 --> 23:40.560
champion of the people, while you're
up here running the racket for him.

23:40.680 --> 23:43.000
And according to your "arrangement",
if anything should happen,

23:43.120 --> 23:45.840
it'd be you who takes the blame,
does the time or swings for it.

23:52.160 --> 23:54.240
- And what do you want?
- I want you...

23:56.080 --> 23:57.360
...to take the opportunity

23:57.480 --> 24:01.040
that God and the New York Stock Exchange
has presented to you.

24:01.160 --> 24:02.320
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

24:02.440 --> 24:04.320
EDNA: Mr Shelby,
the meeting will be starting soon.

24:04.440 --> 24:06.680
Yeah. All right.

24:08.760 --> 24:10.120
Be right there.

24:40.040 --> 24:41.120
ARTHUR: Thank you, Edna.

24:46.280 --> 24:47.720
And shut the door.

24:47.840 --> 24:48.840
(DOOR SLAMS)

24:50.320 --> 24:51.320
(LINDA CLEARS HER THROAT)

24:53.520 --> 24:55.520
OK, now...

24:56.840 --> 24:58.320
Mmm, they're nice.

24:59.480 --> 25:00.480
...let's begin.

25:01.760 --> 25:05.680
Yesterday, as you all know,
there was a fucking terrible...

25:08.000 --> 25:11.280
There was a terrible disaster. Hm?

25:11.400 --> 25:12.640
It wasn't just for us.

25:14.000 --> 25:15.320
It was for the whole world.

25:17.480 --> 25:19.840
Happened in New York.

25:20.920 --> 25:22.080
That's where it happened.

25:22.200 --> 25:23.960
And it slowly spread to London.

25:25.200 --> 25:28.680
And then to, er, fucking Hong Kong. Hm?

25:31.680 --> 25:33.720
Whole thing...whole thing went up.

25:34.720 --> 25:38.320
Well, actually the whole thing
went fucking down but...

25:42.120 --> 25:45.560
...we wasn't the only ones hurt by this.

25:48.160 --> 25:49.200
Whole world is hurt.

25:50.520 --> 25:51.600
A lot of people.

25:53.040 --> 25:54.400
In the papers.

25:54.520 --> 25:56.120
It's all over the news.

25:56.240 --> 25:58.160
- Everyone's talking about it.
- Arthur?

25:59.280 --> 26:01.040
Shouldn't we just wait for Thomas?

26:01.160 --> 26:04.400
Polly, Arthur's now
the chairman of the board.

26:06.280 --> 26:09.360
LEON: Er, Mr Chairman,
perhaps while we wait for Thomas,

26:09.480 --> 26:14.560
I might lighten the gloom and express, as
a relatively new member of this company,

26:14.680 --> 26:17.800
what a pleasure it is to be in a boardroom
that has so many females in it,

26:17.920 --> 26:23.080
and all females who are both
sharp-witted and decorative.

26:23.200 --> 26:26.560
ARTHUR: Yeah, well, we're a very modern
company, Mr Greene.

26:26.680 --> 26:27.640
Indeed.

26:27.760 --> 26:33.120
Although there are still some among us
who cling to their old-fashioned values.

26:33.240 --> 26:34.360
(DOOR OPENS)

26:36.360 --> 26:37.440
How far have we got?

26:38.960 --> 26:41.120
We've established
that ladies are decorative.

26:41.240 --> 26:42.840
ARTHUR: We've only just sat down, Tom.

26:42.960 --> 26:46.840
Actually, um, Arthur has some documents
that he'd like to hand out.

26:46.960 --> 26:48.160
THOMAS: Yeah?

26:48.280 --> 26:49.560
What documents?

26:51.080 --> 26:55.560
I was just explaining to everyone, Tom,
that, um, well, we're fucked.

26:55.680 --> 26:58.800
- Ain't that right? Hm?
- Yes and no. (CLEARS THROAT)

27:00.120 --> 27:03.840
It is true that a large proportion
of the company's funds

27:03.960 --> 27:07.080
were invested in American stocks
and shares.

27:07.200 --> 27:08.440
Invested or hidden?

27:10.240 --> 27:12.520
All investments are approved
by the board, Linda.

27:12.640 --> 27:15.600
Only the ones that went
through the books, Thomas.

27:16.880 --> 27:21.160
Linda, after this meeting there will
be another meeting, for just family.

27:22.320 --> 27:23.360
Did we vote on this?

27:28.560 --> 27:29.520
Arthur?

27:29.640 --> 27:31.040
"Arthur, can't you control your wife?"

27:32.240 --> 27:34.520
We are a very modern company, Mr Greene.

27:38.240 --> 27:41.800
(CLEARS THROAT) To be precise,
everything we channel led

27:41.920 --> 27:45.040
through the New York Stock Exchange
is now offering a return

27:45.160 --> 27:47.360
of ten cents to the dollar.

27:48.560 --> 27:49.800
And the Nolan Bank of America,

27:49.920 --> 27:52.400
where we invested our fluidity,

27:52.520 --> 27:56.320
is offering five cents to the dollar
on all deposits.

27:56.440 --> 27:58.960
- Yeah.
- (SIGHS)

27:59.080 --> 28:01.040
- There is hope.
- Why?

28:01.160 --> 28:03.600
What have you got in there,
a magic wand?

28:07.160 --> 28:11.000
As non executive director of the company,
I need the permission from the chairman

28:11.120 --> 28:13.960
to present my strategy to the board.

28:14.080 --> 28:16.400
Permission granted, Tom.

28:16.520 --> 28:17.520
(SCOFFS)

29:01.880 --> 29:03.880
The Peaky Blinders are coming.

29:04.960 --> 29:06.320
The Peaky Blinders are coming.

29:06.440 --> 29:08.760
Micky,
the Peaky Blinders are coming.

29:11.760 --> 29:16.120
Ladies and gents, Peaky Blinders are
on their way. Please vacate. Thank you.

29:20.040 --> 29:22.520
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

29:28.160 --> 29:30.240
- Good to see you.
- All right, Mr Shelby.

29:30.360 --> 29:31.800
- Mr Shelby...
- Yeah?

29:31.920 --> 29:33.200
...thank you for what you did.

29:33.320 --> 29:34.560
What did I do?

29:34.680 --> 29:37.080
He was going to evict us,
that bastard Fellows.

29:37.200 --> 29:39.560
Now he's cut our rent in half.

29:39.680 --> 29:41.920
Good. Glad to hear it.
Glad to hear it.

29:43.680 --> 29:44.600
All right?

29:44.720 --> 29:47.320
How far can we go, Mr Shelby,
with this beautiful dream?

29:47.440 --> 29:50.480
- All the way, brother. All the way.
- Revolution, man.

29:50.600 --> 29:54.520
This crash, Mr Shelby. They're saying
they're gonna cut my hours.

29:54.640 --> 29:56.960
- Yeah. Where do you work?
- Greenhams Engineering.

29:57.080 --> 29:59.920
Greenham brothers. I know them.
They're not gonna cut your hours.

30:00.040 --> 30:01.800
God bless you. God bless you both.

30:01.920 --> 30:04.360
- Enjoy your drink.
- Gentlemen and ladies.

30:04.480 --> 30:06.560
If you'll all move into the saloon bar,

30:06.680 --> 30:09.000
where you will all be served
a free pint of stingo.

30:09.120 --> 30:10.480
(CHEERING)

30:10.600 --> 30:14.160
Any man who served in France
gets a brandy chaser.

30:14.280 --> 30:16.640
And in spite of what you're reading
in the newspapers,

30:16.760 --> 30:19.840
I want to hear singing and laughing.
Fuck the stock market.

30:19.960 --> 30:21.120
ALL: Fuck the stock market!

30:21.240 --> 30:24.560
They backed the wrong horses,
so fucking what, eh?

30:25.720 --> 30:29.040
Thank you, Mr Shelby. At last,
a politician who gets things done.

30:29.160 --> 30:30.840
You're welcome, brother, you're welcome.

30:30.960 --> 30:32.520
- Get down off the furniture.
- Sorry, Ada.

30:32.640 --> 30:33.960
I was getting excited, wasn't I?

30:38.640 --> 30:39.640
Right.

30:41.560 --> 30:43.560
Can I begin this family meeting
with a proposal?

30:43.680 --> 30:45.680
From now on,
we find somewhere else to meet.

30:45.800 --> 30:47.600
Your husband believes that being seen

30:47.720 --> 30:50.000
mixing with the common people
is good politics.

30:50.120 --> 30:52.480
Hmm. Well, if this is our campaign
for socialism,

30:52.600 --> 30:55.760
perhaps next time, Polly, you won't
wear earrings worth more than the pub.

30:55.880 --> 30:58.720
Right. Family meeting. First item.

30:58.840 --> 31:00.440
This.

31:01.560 --> 31:03.640
Dug out of our Finn's arm yesterday

31:03.760 --> 31:06.160
by Aberama Gold using your gin
and a razor blade.

31:06.280 --> 31:07.840
Finn?

31:07.960 --> 31:09.080
He says they were sent to Limehouse.

31:09.200 --> 31:10.440
Chinatown.

31:10.560 --> 31:12.160
Sent by fucking who?

31:12.280 --> 31:13.400
THOMAS: Sent by me.

31:13.520 --> 31:17.120
I told Finn to stay out of this.
He obviously didn't listen.

31:18.320 --> 31:21.280
Oh, Tommy, sweetheart, I listen to you.

31:21.400 --> 31:25.320
I listen to you when you tell me
no more sport for anyone named Shelby.

31:25.440 --> 31:28.520
I listen to you
when you make me promises.

31:30.360 --> 31:33.320
What's in Chinatown, Tommy?
What the fuck is going on?

31:34.440 --> 31:36.480
£50,000.

31:36.600 --> 31:37.920
In cash.

31:38.040 --> 31:41.080
He said they were sent to Chinatown
to kill somebody.

31:42.160 --> 31:44.480
That kid needs educating, Tommy,
really does.

31:44.600 --> 31:46.040
Jesus Christ, Tommy!

31:46.160 --> 31:48.840
- It was a particular opportunity.
- A particular opportunity

31:48.960 --> 31:51.800
presented to me in confidence.
I dealt with it in confidence.

31:51.920 --> 31:53.960
But you told Polly.

31:54.080 --> 31:58.360
Tommy told me there was
a pimp in East London who sold kids.

31:58.480 --> 32:00.840
THOMAS: Fucking kids, Lizzie, eh? Hm?

32:00.960 --> 32:05.480
This pimp was blackmailing a senior member
of the House of Lords, a very wealthy man.

32:05.600 --> 32:08.360
Now this pimp is lying in a ditch,

32:08.480 --> 32:09.800
covered in flies.

32:09.920 --> 32:11.640
World's a better place.

32:11.760 --> 32:16.320
Holy fuck! So now your business
is improving the world?

32:18.040 --> 32:19.880
Sometimes, Ada...

32:21.040 --> 32:23.080
...killing is a kindness.

32:23.200 --> 32:24.520
Hm?

32:27.120 --> 32:30.040
The man we did the job for
is a High Court judge.

32:30.160 --> 32:34.280
We received intelligence from
a senior police officer in Scotland Yard.

32:34.400 --> 32:37.880
I've made lots of new friends in London.
Men with influence.

32:38.000 --> 32:41.280
The police felt the same way
about this pimp as we did.

32:41.400 --> 32:44.160
He wasn't worth a trial.
The coppers cleared the streets for us.

32:44.280 --> 32:47.800
This was work commissioned
by a High Court judge, by Scotland Yard

32:47.920 --> 32:49.240
and by the House of Lords.

32:49.360 --> 32:51.840
It's a particular opportunity.
It's not to be repeated.

32:51.960 --> 32:54.480
- And it was the right thing to do.
- Fucking right.

32:54.600 --> 32:56.360
Lizzie, you need to understand.

32:56.480 --> 32:58.080
That you tell Polly, not me.

32:58.200 --> 33:03.120
You need to understand that the corridors
of Westminster are very dimly lit.

33:03.240 --> 33:06.560
And for those who make the rules,
there are no rules.

33:06.680 --> 33:09.080
We own the ropes.
Who's going to hang us now, eh?

33:09.200 --> 33:11.280
<i>We? We</i> own the ropes, do we?

33:11.400 --> 33:15.040
Lizzie, Lizzie, if Finn had've listened
to me, you wouldn't have known.

33:15.160 --> 33:17.200
When we go home, I'll explain.

33:18.400 --> 33:20.560
LIZZIE: I can't be bothered
with this shit.

33:25.480 --> 33:26.920
So...

33:27.040 --> 33:31.120
...Tommy Shelby MP. Business as usual.

33:32.200 --> 33:34.160
The strategy I outlined earlier

33:34.280 --> 33:37.800
to rebuild the conventional part
of this business will take time.

33:37.920 --> 33:40.520
- In the meantime...
- Just business as fucking usual.

33:40.640 --> 33:43.240
In the meantime,
it is fortunate that we have maintained

33:43.360 --> 33:45.720
other sources of cash income.

33:45.840 --> 33:49.320
Because until the stock market
recovers, cash is king.

33:49.440 --> 33:50.680
And cash we have.

33:50.800 --> 33:52.520
No-one is gonna hang you, Tommy.

33:52.640 --> 33:54.120
You're gonna hang yourself.

33:56.200 --> 33:59.520
Someone has to pay for them
paintings on your wall, Ada.

33:59.640 --> 34:01.000
Yeah, bye-bye, Ada.

34:01.120 --> 34:04.360
Tommy, you need to go easy on Ada.

34:04.480 --> 34:06.360
Polly...

34:06.480 --> 34:11.280
...when am I ever not easy on Ada, eh?

34:15.720 --> 34:19.480
Thomas, the thing is, Ada...

34:19.600 --> 34:21.680
- She's pregnant.
- (SPLUTTERS)

34:23.600 --> 34:25.520
Ada's what?

34:25.640 --> 34:29.080
These days, people tell me things
without even speaking.

34:29.200 --> 34:30.400
ARTHUR: Wait a minute.

34:30.520 --> 34:31.720
Wait a minute.

34:32.760 --> 34:35.680
Ada's fucking pregnant? Hm?

34:35.800 --> 34:40.760
And, Polly, you need to reassure Ada
that it's 1929, times have changed,

34:40.880 --> 34:43.680
we've a lot to do, and no-one gives a fuck
who the father is.

34:43.800 --> 34:45.000
Really?

34:46.320 --> 34:48.400
I already know who the father is.

34:48.520 --> 34:52.440
But we've had enough shocks for one day.

34:58.920 --> 35:00.160
OK.

35:09.080 --> 35:11.800
All right, go on, then.

35:11.920 --> 35:14.640
How long you known about Ada, huh?

35:14.760 --> 35:15.960
I know her doctor.

35:16.080 --> 35:17.240
He calls me.

35:19.920 --> 35:21.880
Yeah, longer than me.

35:22.000 --> 35:23.080
Have a look at this.

35:30.000 --> 35:32.680
What's that funny writing on there?

35:32.800 --> 35:34.240
Chinese.

35:34.360 --> 35:35.880
Ah, right.

35:38.400 --> 35:39.680
What is it? Hmm?

35:41.240 --> 35:42.240
Bad news?

35:43.280 --> 35:44.400
Maybe.

35:47.000 --> 35:48.240
Angels of Retribution?

35:48.360 --> 35:49.480
Yeah.

35:49.600 --> 35:51.960
Burn the letter they sent.

35:52.080 --> 35:53.480
It's already done.

35:59.000 --> 36:00.520
Look at that, Tom. Hm?

36:02.680 --> 36:04.160
Pulled from our brother, eh?

36:05.840 --> 36:07.600
Finally took a first bullet.

36:08.880 --> 36:10.600
No-one fucking listens to me.

36:15.480 --> 36:16.680
Here, give it here.

36:16.800 --> 36:18.160
I'll keep it for him.

36:18.280 --> 36:20.880
- I still have my first one.
- (CHUCKLES)

36:28.480 --> 36:32.560
Arthur, you can tell our comrades
they can come back in.

36:34.400 --> 36:36.080
Where are you going, brother?

37:10.400 --> 37:13.360
MP: The huge losses
on the British Stock Exchange

37:13.480 --> 37:17.320
will bite into our economy
for the foreseeable future.

37:17.440 --> 37:22.560
I therefore must ask the trade unions
to possess understanding.

37:22.680 --> 37:26.440
The need for their flexibility
and cooperation is paramount

37:26.560 --> 37:30.600
in the coming months as we attempt
to rebuild this great nation.

37:30.720 --> 37:32.560
(MURMURS OF ASSENT)

37:34.200 --> 37:36.000
SPEAKER: Mr Thomas Shelby.

37:37.480 --> 37:38.880
Thank you, Mr Speaker.

37:40.560 --> 37:44.520
My right hon our able friend,
the member for Epping,

37:44.640 --> 37:47.720
asks that following the crash,

37:47.840 --> 37:52.080
trade union members be more flexible
when carrying out their duties.

37:53.920 --> 37:57.240
What he's really asking
is that the working man carry the can.

37:59.480 --> 38:03.320
The grand casino in Monte Carlo
is a small and timid affair

38:03.440 --> 38:08.480
when compared to the wild games of chance
being played in London and New York

38:08.600 --> 38:13.760
by gamblers in silk gloves and beaver
hats, who, when they lose their bets,

38:13.880 --> 38:16.120
turn around and ask the shoe-shine
to pay for it.

38:16.240 --> 38:17.400
(LAUGHTER)

38:17.520 --> 38:21.360
Well, on behalf of the shoe-shines
and can carriers of South Birmingham

38:21.480 --> 38:24.920
and all across Great Britain,
I would suggest

38:25.040 --> 38:29.160
that those who so recklessly lost
their fortunes on the capitalist lottery

38:29.280 --> 38:32.640
- I earn to shine their own shoes...
- (MURMURS OF ASSENT)

38:32.760 --> 38:35.840
...carry their own can
and pay their own bills.

38:35.960 --> 38:36.960
(CHEERING)

38:43.840 --> 38:44.840
Mr Shelby?

38:46.200 --> 38:49.120
I just wanted to say
how much I enjoyed your speech.

38:49.240 --> 38:50.720
You speak very eloquently.

38:50.840 --> 38:52.560
Thank you.

38:52.680 --> 38:57.160
My name's Mosley, by the way.
Oswald Mosley.

38:57.280 --> 38:58.240
Yeah, I know who you are.

38:58.360 --> 39:00.640
My constituency borders yours.

39:00.760 --> 39:04.120
And let me just say,
you've come to my attention.

39:07.240 --> 39:09.080
- (KNOCK ON DOOR)
- Come.

39:13.480 --> 39:14.480
<i>Ah.</i>

39:16.640 --> 39:18.640
I have bad news, Mr...

39:22.520 --> 39:23.520
Shelby.

39:24.800 --> 39:28.440
We agreed 50,000
on completion of business.

39:28.560 --> 39:32.560
My wife and I have had a misfortune
on the London Exchange.

39:32.680 --> 39:34.760
There's 20 there.

39:34.880 --> 39:36.720
You'll have to wait for the rest.

39:41.000 --> 39:42.000
(SIGHS HEAVILY)

39:49.400 --> 39:50.600
Cavalry, eh?

39:50.720 --> 39:52.520
Mm.

39:52.640 --> 39:53.680
Huh!

39:54.920 --> 39:56.000
Yeah.

39:57.160 --> 39:59.560
I spent a long of time
waiting for the cavalry, me.

40:01.960 --> 40:06.760
One time, me and my comrades
waited three days.

40:08.040 --> 40:09.440
When the cavalry finally came,

40:09.560 --> 40:13.200
an officer,
on the back of a fine white horse,

40:13.320 --> 40:18.080
joked that he'd been delayed
playing a game of whist.

40:19.160 --> 40:23.080
So I took out my Webley revolver
and I shot him in the head,

40:23.200 --> 40:25.960
stole his horse,
reported him for cowardice.

40:27.200 --> 40:28.600
All for a game of chance.

40:31.280 --> 40:34.720
After my people completed their task
in Chinatown,

40:34.840 --> 40:38.520
they collected all the photographs,
letters and cheques

40:38.640 --> 40:40.720
that will cause you concern.

40:40.840 --> 40:43.000
I now have them in a safe place.

40:43.120 --> 40:48.880
On Monday, you will give me
the full £50,000 in cash...

40:50.040 --> 40:52.680
...or I will steal your white horse
from under you.

40:54.320 --> 40:58.600
How the fuck did a man like you
get into a position of trust

40:58.720 --> 41:01.280
in a place of power and privilege?

41:01.400 --> 41:02.840
A man like me?

41:07.600 --> 41:08.600
A man like me?

41:10.120 --> 41:11.880
Lord Suckerby.

41:12.000 --> 41:13.400
I've seen the photographs.

41:16.080 --> 41:17.080
Monday.

41:23.840 --> 41:25.480
(SHOUTS) Shelby!

41:26.800 --> 41:28.440
Sorry I'm late, Ada.

41:28.560 --> 41:31.240
We've been having briefings
from the Home Office.

41:31.360 --> 41:34.640
The police are concerned about the effect
of the crash in industrial areas.

41:34.760 --> 41:37.000
- Right.
- Everything all right?

41:37.120 --> 41:38.640
Yeah, fine.

41:38.760 --> 41:41.080
We lost money in New York,
so I've been up late.

41:42.160 --> 41:43.200
Your brother been busy?

41:44.160 --> 41:47.640
Er, he's had two meetings with
Mr Shapurji Saklatvala,

41:47.760 --> 41:49.760
the former Communist MP
for Battersea.

41:49.880 --> 41:52.480
He's been approached
by an anarchist group in Walsall -

41:52.600 --> 41:53.720
he's setting up a meeting -

41:53.840 --> 41:57.800
and there's talk of a mass walk-out
of bus drivers, Nottingham and Derby,

41:57.920 --> 42:02.560
organised by two Communist convenors
not formerly known to Special Branch.

42:02.680 --> 42:05.600
He's also had a telephone conversation
with Jessie Eden,

42:05.720 --> 42:09.240
who is organising a committee
to resist wage cuts across the city.

42:09.360 --> 42:11.760
But he'll report more when he sees her.

42:11.880 --> 42:13.000
It's all in there, though.

42:13.120 --> 42:14.560
Names and everything.

42:14.680 --> 42:17.320
I heard he had the Labour benches
roaring approval in the House today.

42:17.440 --> 42:21.000
Huh. If only he meant it,
he'd be dangerous.

42:21.120 --> 42:24.360
Didn't know you drank stout, Ada.
Thought it was gin.

42:24.480 --> 42:26.480
Times are hard.

42:28.040 --> 42:30.000
Hm.

42:31.920 --> 42:34.120
Exactly how much did you lose?

42:35.320 --> 42:37.760
Don't worry about it. Tommy has a plan.

42:37.880 --> 42:41.920
He thinks that we can turn the collapse
of the stock exchange to our advantage.

42:42.040 --> 42:45.480
He says, "When others retreat,
you advance."

42:45.600 --> 42:48.920
He says, "We can wave cash in the faces
of desperate men."

42:50.920 --> 42:53.440
Tell your brother from me,
he's doing excellent work.

42:53.560 --> 42:57.840
I'm told two more military contracts
for vehicles

42:57.960 --> 43:00.960
and parts for the Army in India
are on their way to him.

43:15.880 --> 43:17.520
(EXHALES)

43:17.640 --> 43:18.640
Fuck.

43:25.120 --> 43:26.480
- (KNOCK ON DOOR)
- Come.

43:26.600 --> 43:29.120
Mr Shelby, this arrived from New York.

43:29.240 --> 43:30.880
It's from Winston Churchill.

43:32.360 --> 43:35.560
He says he was in New York
and had dinner with Charlie Chaplin

43:35.680 --> 43:37.880
and Chaplin mentioned your name.

43:38.000 --> 43:40.840
So he was in New York
and he doesn't mention the crash.

43:40.960 --> 43:43.360
No. Even though, in the bar last night,

43:43.480 --> 43:48.360
Mr Churchill's private secretary
reckoned he lost £75,000 in two hours.

43:50.600 --> 43:51.600
And you?

43:53.240 --> 43:56.200
Were you affected, Mr Shelby?

43:56.320 --> 43:58.600
I'm going to my apartment, Adam.

43:58.720 --> 43:59.640
You lock up.

43:59.760 --> 44:03.720
Sorry, Mr Shelby, you...
you have one more appointment.

44:03.840 --> 44:06.240
You set it yourself.
It's in the diary from last week.

44:06.360 --> 44:07.840
<i>A</i> journalist from the <i>Times.</i>

44:07.960 --> 44:09.720
He used to be with
the <i>Birmingham Mail.</i>

44:09.840 --> 44:11.600
He sent you some questions.

44:11.720 --> 44:13.560
You said you wanted to meet him.

44:13.680 --> 44:14.680
He's outside.

44:15.760 --> 44:16.760
Yes.

44:17.880 --> 44:18.960
Send him in.

44:23.240 --> 44:27.440
Mr Shelby?
Mr Levitt from the <i>London Times.</i>

44:27.560 --> 44:29.280
Have a seat.

44:29.400 --> 44:31.400
Adam, you go home, I'll lock up.

44:37.040 --> 44:40.480
Mr Shelby, do you remember me?

44:42.600 --> 44:44.240
No.

44:44.360 --> 44:49.160
Once, in Small Heath,
you were burning photographs of the King.

44:49.280 --> 44:55.400
<i>- London Times.</i> You've done well.
- As have you, sir, to put it mildly.

44:55.520 --> 44:57.640
I sent you a list of questions.

44:57.760 --> 44:59.840
Yeah, I misplaced them.

45:01.040 --> 45:02.960
Yeah, well, you have a lot on your plate.

45:03.080 --> 45:04.280
Yes.

45:04.400 --> 45:07.200
All I remember is
that your questions interested me.

45:07.320 --> 45:09.080
Oh!

45:09.200 --> 45:10.480
Good.

45:11.720 --> 45:13.440
Sorry, just...

45:13.560 --> 45:15.160
Ah, here we are.

45:16.160 --> 45:17.720
Yes, um... (CLEARS THROAT)

45:19.480 --> 45:24.840
Um... So, Mr Shelby,
traditionally in this country,

45:24.960 --> 45:29.760
print journalists take no interest in the,
er, the private lives of politicians.

45:29.880 --> 45:31.840
Private lives?

45:31.960 --> 45:36.040
But in these modern times,
especially in America...

45:36.160 --> 45:40.920
...journalists are beginning to...
Well, that is to say, yes, um...

45:41.040 --> 45:42.920
Readers are beginning to say...

45:43.960 --> 45:47.200
...want to know more about the men
who represent them.

45:47.320 --> 45:48.600
Of course.

45:48.720 --> 45:50.640
In these modern times.

45:51.720 --> 45:55.000
Whereas before it would have
been seen as ungentlemanly to, er,

45:55.120 --> 45:58.920
to ask a public figure questions
about personal matters

45:59.040 --> 46:01.920
- or business affairs.
- Oh, well. No need to worry.

46:02.040 --> 46:03.560
I'm no gentleman.

46:07.360 --> 46:08.520
Hm.

46:10.280 --> 46:11.880
Er, Mr Shelby,
as I said in my letter,

46:12.000 --> 46:14.720
ten years ago I was a journalist
on the <i>Birmingham Evening Mail.</i>

46:16.920 --> 46:19.080
And of course, working in that city,

46:19.200 --> 46:22.000
it was impossible
not to know your name...

46:23.640 --> 46:26.080
...and your reputation.

46:29.000 --> 46:31.840
(EXHALES) So, when I saw that you had
been elected as a socialist...

46:31.960 --> 46:33.280
You reflected on the fact

46:33.400 --> 46:39.080
that working people can indeed change
their lives for the better...

46:40.400 --> 46:44.720
...channel their abilities in new
directions, discover better methods,

46:44.840 --> 46:50.200
aim for happier outcomes,
even win awards for industry.

46:50.320 --> 46:52.080
You can write this down, Mr Levitt.

46:52.200 --> 46:55.600
The question I have for you,
Mr Shelby, is this.

46:57.160 --> 47:02.040
Was your conversion from bookmaker
to socialist politician

47:02.160 --> 47:05.040
a gradual thing or...

47:06.400 --> 47:09.960
...a road to Damascus experience?

47:11.040 --> 47:12.720
Yeah.

47:12.840 --> 47:14.720
Now I hear that question...

47:16.640 --> 47:18.240
...I remember receiving your letters

47:18.360 --> 47:21.520
and I distinctly remember your use
of the word "bookmaker".

47:22.880 --> 47:26.040
- Were you not a bookmaker, sir?
- Yes.

47:26.160 --> 47:30.440
I gained a licence
in 1919 for on-track betting.

47:30.560 --> 47:31.800
But, since 1923,

47:31.920 --> 47:35.360
I've made my fortune in the manufacture,
sale and export of motor cars.

47:35.480 --> 47:36.920
And lately gin.

47:37.040 --> 47:40.520
And lately three new homes
for orphaned children.

47:42.680 --> 47:45.240
You can write all this down, Mr Levitt.

47:46.520 --> 47:49.160
I have another question, Mr Shelby.

47:49.280 --> 47:53.760
In Birmingham,
at the time that I was there,

47:53.880 --> 47:56.120
there was a Major Campbell.

47:57.440 --> 47:58.640
He was found dead.

47:59.720 --> 48:01.720
A member of your family was charged.

48:05.880 --> 48:07.000
(CHUCKLES)

48:11.040 --> 48:13.880
Right, you answer me this.
Answer me this.

48:16.320 --> 48:19.880
What is your Tory newspaper
more afraid of?

48:20.000 --> 48:22.520
Is it evolution or revolution?

48:22.640 --> 48:26.160
And what is it about
working-class men like me,

48:26.280 --> 48:29.640
standing up in the House of Commons
and speaking from the heart,

48:29.760 --> 48:34.760
what is it that so troubles you
that you would try to undermine me?

48:34.880 --> 48:37.120
I am talking about specific events, sir.

48:37.240 --> 48:38.240
Which I don't recall...

48:39.680 --> 48:42.360
...with which I was never
personally linked,

48:42.480 --> 48:45.960
and after which
all convictions were quashed.

48:52.440 --> 48:57.440
Yeah, now...
I recall receiving your letter...

48:58.920 --> 49:00.880
...and I recall that when I did...

49:02.400 --> 49:06.720
...I asked a colleague of mine
to carry out some research.

49:09.560 --> 49:10.640
Just a moment.

49:16.040 --> 49:18.720
Here we are. (EXHALES)

49:27.240 --> 49:29.840
Ah, Michael Levitt.

49:29.960 --> 49:30.960
Correct?

49:32.240 --> 49:34.360
- Yes.
- Yes.

49:34.480 --> 49:35.920
Journalist.

49:36.040 --> 49:38.040
Unmarried.

49:38.160 --> 49:40.000
An apartment in Maida Vale.

49:41.000 --> 49:44.520
An apartment opposite
the underground station.

49:46.560 --> 49:49.360
"Unmarried" is underlined.

49:49.480 --> 49:52.560
Mr Levitt enjoys walks in the park.

49:52.680 --> 49:54.200
Sometimes alone.

49:54.320 --> 49:56.360
Sometimes not alone.

49:57.920 --> 50:00.160
Sometimes with other men.

50:05.960 --> 50:10.200
Sometimes with other men.

50:12.960 --> 50:16.680
I'm old-fashioned...Michael.

50:17.720 --> 50:20.320
I believe private lives
should remain private.

50:21.560 --> 50:24.000
Not everything modern is good, now, is it?

50:28.360 --> 50:29.640
You gonna write this down...

50:31.240 --> 50:33.200
...in your little fucking book?

50:41.240 --> 50:42.800
Well?

50:42.920 --> 50:44.720
Not yet.

50:44.840 --> 50:46.520
I didn't tell him.

50:46.640 --> 50:49.920
Him knowing or not knowing
has no relevance to what we're drinking.

50:51.440 --> 50:52.480
It's vintage.

50:53.920 --> 50:57.120
- Fuck it.
- (CHUCKLES)

50:57.240 --> 50:58.560
This...

51:00.280 --> 51:01.520
...is for us.

51:03.800 --> 51:05.400
Let's drink to the baby.

51:08.080 --> 51:10.200
Polly, do you remember
when I was last pregnant?

51:12.560 --> 51:14.680
You were going to take me to Cardiff.

51:14.800 --> 51:16.760
I was going to get rid of it.

51:17.840 --> 51:19.040
What about this time?

51:22.640 --> 51:23.840
Imagine.

51:26.360 --> 51:28.120
The father's scared.

51:28.240 --> 51:29.920
He runs away.

51:30.040 --> 51:31.200
You're left.

51:33.400 --> 51:35.480
Oh, sweetheart.

51:35.600 --> 51:40.800
The baby's black,
he's a bastard and it's Birmingham.

51:42.440 --> 51:43.760
But you don't care.

51:44.880 --> 51:47.280
Because the world has changed.

51:48.720 --> 51:51.040
And the baby's eyes are golden.

51:51.160 --> 51:55.840
And you're gonna leave her with
Aunt Polly every day to look after.

51:55.960 --> 51:59.200
Aunt Polly, who insisted
that you called her Elizabeth.

51:59.320 --> 52:01.400
How do you know it's a her?

52:01.520 --> 52:04.560
Cos I'm Polly Gray.

52:04.680 --> 52:06.440
It's a girl?

52:06.560 --> 52:07.560
Golden.

52:08.760 --> 52:12.040
To be born in the year 1930,

52:12.160 --> 52:14.880
where everything will be changed
for the better.

52:16.640 --> 52:19.520
She'll be the colour of a Hollywood Oscar.

52:22.760 --> 52:24.200
What will Tommy say?

52:27.440 --> 52:29.080
Tommy knows.

52:32.440 --> 52:33.760
Hmm!

52:33.880 --> 52:38.600
He's also seen that the world's
big and round and he says, "So what?"

52:43.600 --> 52:45.720
Tommy is right, you know, Ada.

52:47.160 --> 52:49.560
We are flying above the rules now.

52:52.520 --> 52:54.960
We're bold people, aren't we, Polly?

52:56.600 --> 52:57.880
That's the beauty.

53:12.320 --> 53:13.320
Hello, Cyril.

53:15.120 --> 53:17.040
Least you're still talking to me.

53:27.000 --> 53:28.080
Where is everyone?

53:28.200 --> 53:30.040
Your wife is upstairs with Ruby.

53:33.520 --> 53:39.840
You know, Frances, if there were to be
a snap election in this house today...

53:41.440 --> 53:42.720
...wouldn't win it...

53:43.760 --> 53:46.600
...not even if I were running
against the devil himself.

53:46.720 --> 53:47.720
No.

53:48.760 --> 53:49.960
- I gathered.
- Mm.

53:51.680 --> 53:53.280
Where's Charles?

53:53.400 --> 53:54.640
Charles is in the stable.

53:56.760 --> 53:58.080
Thank you.

54:15.080 --> 54:16.480
(CLEARS THROAT)

54:18.000 --> 54:19.440
Did Arthur explain?

54:19.560 --> 54:21.400
He said it's God's will.

54:23.320 --> 54:24.880
But you're not God!

54:35.520 --> 54:37.760
(SIGHS) No, I'm not God.

54:42.720 --> 54:43.840
Not yet.

54:43.864 --> 54:48.864
http://hiqve.com/
